and I know that towards
the end of Trajectory,

00:41:47.040 --> 00:41:48.350
there's a beautiful passage.

00:41:48.350 --> 00:41:50.780
There was a passage
in one of the stories

00:41:50.780 --> 00:41:55.190
where you reference Nick
Carraway, but I'd like to sort

00:41:55.190 --> 00:41:57.960
of spin off of the question
on what you're reading now

00:41:57.960 --> 00:42:01.820
and ask what shaped
both of you .

00:42:01.820 --> 00:42:06.240
What literary lights
made you the way you are?

00:42:06.240 --> 00:42:10.710
Which is wonderful, both of you.

00:42:10.710 --> 00:42:12.010
&gt;&gt; Richard Russo: No, go.

00:42:12.010 --> 00:42:13.530
Go, go.

00:42:13.530 --> 00:42:15.790
&gt;&gt; Lorrie Moore:
You know, I don't --

00:42:15.790 --> 00:42:21.450
personally, I don't really
feel that I'm shaped.

00:42:21.450 --> 00:42:23.980
I know I'm shaped by everything.

00:42:23.980 --> 00:42:27.830
Is the question really
over here?

00:42:27.830 --> 00:42:29.130
&gt;&gt; Kevin Larimer:
She's right there.

00:42:29.130 --> 00:42:30.430
&gt;&gt; Lorrie Moore: Over there?

00:42:30.430 --> 00:42:31.730
&gt;&gt; Richard Russo: Oh, yeah.

00:42:31.730 --> 00:42:33.030
Oh, hi.

00:42:33.030 --> 00:42:34.330
&gt;&gt; Lorrie Moore: Okay.

00:42:34.330 --> 00:42:35.630
All right.

00:42:35.630 --> 00:42:36.930
But I'm sure I'm shaped by
everything that I really like.

00:42:36.930 --> 00:42:38.230
It's all food.

00:42:38.230 --> 00:42:39.530
It all goes in.

00:42:39.530 --> 00:42:41.950
It all nourishes you.

00:42:41.950 --> 00:42:45.900
There are some times
when I've explicitly sort

00:42:45.900 --> 00:42:49.280
of done a bounce off of
another writer's story,

00:42:49.280 --> 00:42:51.160
and it still doesn't
seem anything

00:42:51.160 --> 00:42:52.890
like that writer's story.

00:42:52.890 --> 00:42:56.940
It's not. So I mean one
has literary heroes.

00:42:56.940 --> 00:43:02.840
I don't think that one's
work is necessarily formed

00:43:02.840 --> 00:43:04.680
by them at all.

00:43:04.680 --> 00:43:07.260
If only. That would be so great.

00:43:07.260 --> 00:43:14.420
But you take a little
inspiration just by virtue

00:43:14.420 --> 00:43:17.930
of the fact that you know
there are things in the world

00:43:17.930 --> 00:43:21.450
that are this beautiful
to read, and you just want

00:43:21.450 --> 00:43:24.730
to also be part of that project.

00:43:24.730 --> 00:43:28.370
So go ahead.

00:43:28.370 --> 00:43:29.670
&gt;&gt; Richard Russo: My
novel Straight Man begins

00:43:29.670 --> 00:43:32.690
with an epigraph
from Fitzgerald.

00:43:32.690 --> 00:43:33.990
Is it Myrtle, I think?

00:43:33.990 --> 00:43:35.290
Who is it?

00:43:35.290 --> 00:43:38.420
Early in the book, they're at
a party and Nick is talking

00:43:38.420 --> 00:43:43.020
to this woman, Myrtle, who
has a dog, and she says --

00:43:43.020 --> 00:43:48.230
it's just such brilliant
dialogue.

00:43:48.230 --> 00:43:53.610
She says they're nice to have,
a dog, and I love the way

00:43:53.610 --> 00:43:59.680
that goes from the plural
"they" to the singular "a dog."

00:43:59.680 --> 00:44:02.680
There's something about
that that's just so rich

00:44:02.680 --> 00:44:04.410
with that woman's voice.

00:44:04.410 --> 00:44:09.530
That shift from the plural
to the singular locates her

00:44:09.530 --> 00:44:16.280
in terms of class, and it's
just wonderful, and you pick

00:44:16.280 --> 00:44:18.260
up little things like
that wherever you go,

00:44:18.260 --> 00:44:19.560
wherever you read.

00:44:19.560 --> 00:44:22.960
You find little things.

00:44:22.960 --> 00:44:26.050
I think most writers read
with larceny in their hearts,

00:44:26.050 --> 00:44:28.350
and it's not that
you're going to --

00:44:28.350 --> 00:44:31.370
it's not that you're going to
steal it now and use it now.

00:44:31.370 --> 00:44:35.930
It's that you put it away
in that little closet

00:44:35.930 --> 00:44:41.180
and you think that'll, you
know, do me well at some point

00:44:41.180 --> 00:44:43.270
if I remember it, and
I remember, I think --

00:44:43.270 --> 00:44:45.860
I remember thinking that
way about Fitzgerald, too,

00:44:45.860 --> 00:44:48.410
in terms of The Great
Gatsby, understanding really

00:44:48.410 --> 00:44:51.140
for the first time
what the difference is

00:44:51.140 --> 00:44:54.640
between a book being about
a character and a book being

00:44:54.640 --> 00:44:57.460
that character's story,
because that's a stark example

00:44:57.460 --> 00:44:59.240
of that, isn't it?

00:44:59.240 --> 00:45:01.500
It's about Gatsby, but
it's not Gatsby's story,

00:45:01.500 --> 00:45:05.470
it's Nick's story, and I think
it was that book that I began

00:45:05.470 --> 00:45:08.320
to -- I mean I understood
it kind of intellectually,

00:45:08.320 --> 00:45:09.620
the way we do sometimes.

00:45:09.620 --> 00:45:11.000
You'll understand something.

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:15.430
But it made sense to me, I
think, for the first time.

00:45:15.430 --> 00:45:17.260
&gt;&gt; Kevin Larimer: Okay,
another question over here.

00:45:17.260 --> 00:45:18.590
&gt;&gt; All right.

00:45:18.590 --> 00:45:22.050
Thank you for a wonderful
and funny conversation today.

00:45:22.050 --> 00:45:25.340
I didn't expect it
would be this funny.

00:45:25.340 --> 00:45:28.710
So I was wondering -- you
talked about how stories grow

00:45:28.710 --> 00:45:32.680
up in your hands, and sometimes
they turn into short stories

00:45:32.680 --> 00:45:36.580
or novels, but I was
wondering, what is that moment

00:45:36.580 --> 00:45:40.430
like when the story
is born in your head?

00:45:40.430 --> 00:45:43.080
Like one minute, it's not
there, and the other minute,

00:45:43.080 --> 00:45:46.070
it's there, and what is that
-- where is it coming from?

00:45:46.070 --> 00:45:50.280
Where is that light of
ray coming into your head

00:45:50.280 --> 00:45:54.870
and bringing this
beautiful story to existence?

00:45:54.870 --> 00:46:00.190
&gt;&gt; Lorrie Moore: I think for
me -- I mean for every writer,

00:46:00.190 --> 00:46:01.850
it's a little different.

00:46:01.850 --> 00:46:05.290
For me, stories begin
with an emotion.

00:46:05.290 --> 00:46:09.390
I mean sometimes it's language
and characters and voice

00:46:09.390 --> 00:46:13.580
and setting that sort of
spur you on, but for me,

00:46:13.580 --> 00:46:17.150
I'm very interested in
a complicated emotion

00:46:17.150 --> 00:46:20.530
and what kind of story
could contain that --

00:46:20.530 --> 00:46:26.560
not express it, not describe
it, but actually contain it,

00:46:26.560 --> 00:46:30.860
so that a reader could
walk into a narrative

00:46:30.860 --> 00:46:33.700
and have that same feeling.

00:46:33.700 --> 00:46:36.400
I think I've lost the
questioner in the lights.

00:46:36.400 --> 00:46:37.700
There you are.

00:46:37.700 --> 00:46:40.110
&gt;&gt; Kevin Larimer: She sat down.

00:46:40.110 --> 00:46:41.410
There she is.

00:46:41.410 --> 00:46:42.710
&gt;&gt; Lorrie Moore:
Wrap it up, it says.

00:46:42.710 --> 00:46:44.010
&gt;&gt; Richard Russo: Yeah.

00:46:44.010 --> 00:46:45.310
&gt;&gt; Lorrie Moore: Okay.

00:46:45.310 --> 00:46:46.610
Here, you go.

00:46:46.610 --> 00:46:49.490
So and then once you have that
emotion and you build a world

00:46:49.490 --> 00:46:53.800
that can contain it and
a voice, you wrap it.

00:46:54.850 --> 00:46:56.150
&gt;&gt; Kevin Larimer: Wow.

00:46:56.150 --> 00:46:57.450
Wrong lights.

00:46:57.450 --> 00:46:58.750
&gt;&gt; Richard Russo:
Yeah, now they're --

00:46:58.750 --> 00:47:00.050
&gt;&gt; Kevin Larimer: Wrong lights.

00:47:00.050 --> 00:47:01.350
Okay.

00:47:01.350 --> 00:47:02.650
&gt;&gt; Richard Russo: Yeah,
we're supposed to wrap it up,

00:47:02.650 --> 00:47:06.040
so I'll just say very
quickly I agree with Lorrie.

00:47:06.040 --> 00:47:09.930
Those moments, the aha
moment in the story,

00:47:09.930 --> 00:47:15.250
it'll come at different
times in different books.

00:47:15.250 --> 00:47:17.190
Sometimes it'll be a
character revelation.

00:47:17.190 --> 00:47:19.360
Sometimes it'll be something.

00:47:19.360 --> 00:47:22.890
I remember very distinctly
in Empire Falls,

00:47:22.890 --> 00:47:25.990
there was a moment, and I was at
least halfway through the book,

00:47:25.990 --> 00:47:30.810
when I thought to myself oh,
this book is about cruelty,

00:47:30.810 --> 00:47:36.010
and I didn't know that
before, and so we love those.

00:47:36.010 --> 00:47:38.240
We love those, when suddenly
we know something today

00:47:38.240 --> 00:47:43.420
that we didn't know yesterday,
but it comes, and it's different

00:47:43.420 --> 00:47:44.720
in each book, I think.

00:47:44.720 --> 00:47:46.380
&gt;&gt; Lorrie Moore: Rachel Cusk
says every good story is

00:47:46.380 --> 00:47:47.680
about cruelty.

00:47:47.680 --> 00:47:52.780
&gt;&gt; Richard Russo: I wouldn't
necessarily disagree with that.

00:47:52.780 --> 00:47:54.080
&gt;&gt; Lorrie Moore: I know.

00:47:54.080 --> 00:47:56.830
I know. I think it's
worth thinking about.

00:47:56.830 --> 00:47:58.980
&gt;&gt; Kevin Larimer: Thank
you all for coming.

00:47:58.980 --> 00:48:00.280
&gt;&gt; Richard Russo: Thank you.

00:48:00.280 --> 00:48:02.600
&gt;&gt; Kevin Larimer: Thank
you, Richard, Laurie.

00:48:02.600 --> 00:48:03.900
Thank you.

